     SECTION 2: WHY THIS AREA
════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<section style="background:var(--color-base, #f2ead4); padding:80px 24px;">
  <div style="max-width:800px; margin:0 auto;">
    <p style="font-family:var(--font-sans); font-size:0.75rem; font-weight:700; letter-spacing:0.15em; text-transform:uppercase; color:#b98229; margin-bottom:1rem;">Local Expertise</p>
    <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif); font-size:clamp(1.8rem, 3.5vw, 2.8rem); font-weight:300; line-height:1.2; color:#191817; margin-bottom:1.75rem;">Brisbane's inner west riverside precinct.</h2>
    <p style="font-family:var(--font-sans); font-size:1rem; font-weight:300; line-height:1.8; color:#4a4540; margin-bottom:1.25rem;">
      St Lucia sits roughly five kilometres west of the CBD, with the Brisbane River tracing its southern and south-eastern boundary. It is a suburb with two distinct demand profiles operating in parallel: owner-occupiers drawn to character Queenslanders and post-war homes on generous western-precinct blocks, and investors targeting UQ-anchored rental yield from post-graduate and professional tenants. This dual market dynamic means St Lucia rarely sits quiet. When owner-occupier competition softens, investor demand tends to hold, and vice versa. Sellers who understand which buyer pool their property speaks to, and who position accordingly, are the ones who extract the strongest results.
    </p>
<!-- APPRAISAL FORM -->
