    <p style="font-family:var(--font-sans); font-size:1rem; font-weight:300; line-height:1.8; color:#4a4540; margin-bottom:1.25rem;">
      Value in St Lucia is driven by several converging factors. UQ proximity is the dominant consideration for investors: the post-graduate and professional rental pool is deep, with tenant demand remaining consistent across market cycles. For owner-occupiers, the calculus is different: character home integrity, river access on the suburb's southern streets, block size, and school catchment are what move the needle. Brisbane State High School is a significant catchment driver for families at the upper end of the budget, and Toowong State School catchment adds a secondary pull. North-facing blocks on the elevated western streets also carry a meaningful premium above the suburb's baseline.
    </p>
    <p style="font-family:var(--font-sans); font-size:1rem; font-weight:300; line-height:1.8; color:#4a4540; margin-bottom:1.25rem;">
      Selling in St Lucia well requires understanding which buyer type your property will attract most strongly, and then building the campaign around that profile. An original Queenslander on a 700-square-metre western block is a family and lifestyle story first. A well-tenanted unit close to the UQ campus with documented yield history is an investor proposition. The two require different pricing strategy, different marketing emphasis, and different timing. A campaign that tries to speak to both equally often ends up compelling to neither. The strongest results here come from clarity of positioning and a genuine understanding of the active buyer pools on both sides of the market.
    </p>
    <div style="display:flex; gap:1.5rem; flex-wrap:wrap;">
      <div style="flex:1; min-width:200px; background:#fff; padding:1.75rem; border-left:3px solid #b98229;">
